node.text: @kiacooks credits her mom and grandma for instilling in her a love of good food and cooking, and in today’s episode of Secret Family Recipe, Kia makes one of her grandma’s signature dishes, Chicken & Stuff, with an assist from her mom. Along the way, Kia tweaks things here and there (blanched green beans instead of canned; sautéed chicken instead of boiled) to make the recipe her own while she and her mom talk about the origins of this delicious dish with the whimsical name. Tap the link in our bio for Kia’s family recipe. #thekitchn

node.text: Bacalao (salted cod fish) is a kitchen staple in Puerto Rican households often used in cold salads, stewed with a savory tomato sauce and served with boiled root vegetables, battered and fried for bacalaitos, or cooked with rice to make this delicious and comforting arroz con bacalao. Tap the link in our bio for @thesofritoproject’s recipe, which also includes a small batch of sofrito, the herbaceous, aromatic seasoning blend that’s the foundation of many Puerto Rican dishes. The sofrito can be frozen for up to six months, so prep it now, freeze it, then use it to add Puerto Rican flavor to stews, soups, beans, and more. (Image: @ambergressphotography, Styling: @krack513, Props: @vanessalvazquez) #thekitchn

node.text:
“For many Latinx folks living in the U.S., having a dual identity — one foot in and one foot out of the culture — is a way of life. Navigating that can be difficult, but I find that the simplest way to stay true to my Puerto Rican and Afro-Caribbean roots is through food,” writes guest editor Reina Gascon-Lopez, the chef behind @thesofritoproject. “I love making dishes that I grew up eating that remind me of loved ones. Many recipes were passed down from generation to generation, adapted by the cooks before me and then tweaked again by me to make them my own.” 

The cooks and recipe developers showcased in Reina’s Latinx and Hispanic Heritage Month series live all over the country, and represent different communities throughout the diaspora: Honduras, the Dominican Republic, Cuba, and Puerto Rico. “These dishes are all very different, but seeing the connections among the recipes is truly special. We all have something to bring to the table that can express our multi-layered identities without limiting ourselves in the process.” Tap the link in our bio for Reina’s essay. (Illustration: @isabela.humphrey) #thekitchn

node.text: If you’ve ever tried to spread cold, straight-out-of-the-fridge butter on toast using a mere butter knife, you now how fruitless it can be. Instead of beautifully, evenly buttered toast, you get splotchy, torn bread with some butter here and clumps of butter there. Luckily, there’ are gadgets for that! Ones that promise to spread cold butter just *like that* — no tears, no problems, no buttery dreams dashed. 🧈 Of course, @riddley_s had to know if they worked, so she tried 5 — and the winner is only $5.
